text:
However many doubts and doubts about doubts that you can multiply, a case of doubt in a private domain is unclean, and in a public domain it is deemed clean. 
How so? One who entered an alley  and an unclean thing was in the courtyard, and a doubt arose as to whether he entered or did not enter [the courtyard];   
Or if an unclean thing was in a house and there is doubt whether he entered or did not enter; 
Or even if he entered, there is doubt whether the unclean thing was there or not; 
Or even if it was there, there is doubt whether it consisted of the prescribed minimum or not; 
Or even if it consisted of the prescribed minimum, there is doubt whether it was unclean or clean; 
Or even if it was unclean, there is doubt whether he touched it or not;
Any such case of doubt is deemed unclean. 
Rabbi Eliezer says: if there is a doubt whether he entered, he is clean, but if there is a doubt whether he touched it, he is unclean.
